frontends: restore IPv4/IPv6 offload parity in the ported/non-ported/sync paths

A v4/v6 audit of the ported, non-ported and connection-sync NSS frontends
found five non-protocol-inherent asymmetries where one family accelerates,
counts or classifies a flow differently from its sibling. All are upstream
copy/paste drift (present in the pristine CodeLinaro pin and in QSDK 14.0.r8),
none are corrected by the existing patch stack. Fix each by mirroring the
correct sibling:

1. ecm_nss_ipv6.c UDP stats-sync: the IPv4 path promotes a reply-seen
   accelerated UDP flow to the conntrack 'stream' state (IPS_SEEN_REPLY +
   IPS_ASSURED) before applying UDP_CT_REPLIED; the IPv6 path applies the
   timeout but never sets the bits. Consequence: accelerated IPv6 UDP flows
   are never marked ASSURED, so they stay eligible for early_drop eviction
   under conntrack-table pressure (risking teardown of long-lived offloaded
   v6 UDP flows), and the !ASSURED-guarded block re-runs on every sync. Set
   both bits to match IPv4.

2. ecm_nss_ipv6.c multicast conn-sync totals: the return-direction
   bytes/packets are accounted with is_from=true (like the flow direction),
   double-counting them into from_data_total and never updating to_data_total.
   IPv4 passes false for the return call. Pass false.

3. ecm_non_ported_ipv4.c is_protocol_supported(): EtherIP (IP proto 97, a
   dual-stack encapsulation) is accepted by the IPv6 non-ported gate but not
   the IPv4 one, so EtherIP-over-IPv4 is exceptioned to the host while
   EtherIP-over-IPv6 is accelerated. ecm_interface_is_tunnel_endpoint()
   already treats IPPROTO_ETHERIP family-agnostically and the NSS frontend
   passes tuple.protocol generically, so add the IPv4 case to match IPv6.

4. ecm_ported_ipv6.c AE-result switch: the IPv4 file sets
   ECM_FRONT_END_ENGINE_FLAG_AE_PRECEDENCE in both the AE_CLASSIFIER_RESULT_NONE
   and _DONT_CARE cases before allocating from the precedence array; the IPv6
   file sets it in neither, so when an external AE classifier is registered an
   IPv6 precedence-allocated connection switches AE differently from its IPv4
   twin. Set the (family-agnostic) flag on both v6 cases to match v4.

5. ecm_nss_ported_ipv6.c to-interface DSA case: the egress VLAN tag is written
   from vlan_value (the VLAN-case local, 0 here) instead of dsa_vlan_value
   (the DSA tag just computed two lines above), so a DSA egress interface on a
   v6 flow would be offloaded with egress VLAN 0. IPv4's to-side DSA case and
   the v6 from-side DSA case both use dsa_vlan_value; use it here too.

Signed-off-by: Julius Bairaktaris <julius@bairaktaris.de>

